<HEADLINE>
FT  14 NOV 94 / FT Guide To US Interest Rates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Why is everyone so sure that US interest rates are going up tomorrow?
The Federal Open Markets Committee, which sets interest rate policy for the
US Federal Reserve, meets tomorrow in Washington for the first time in
nearly two months. It has raised interest rates five times this year, most
recently on August 16, in an effort to control an economy that grew at an
annualised rate of 4.1 per cent in the second quarter and to head off
inflationary pressures before they had a chance to show up as higher prices.
Since then, it has become clear that the US economy is still growing much
faster than the 2 1/2 per cent pace that most members of the FOMC would
regard as sustainable - a 3.4 per cent rate in the third quarter. The
unemployment rate is down to 5.8 per cent - at or below the level at which
most FOMC members expect employers will start having difficulty finding
workers and having to pay higher wages - and some commodity prices are
rising fast. As a result, virtually everyone agrees that the Fed needs to
pour another jug of cold water on the economy in the form of higher interest
rates.
Who makes the decision?
The FOMC is made up of the seven members of the board of governors, who are
appointed by the president for a 14-year term, and a rotating sample of five
of the presidents of the 12 regional Federal Reserve banks. The committee is
chaired by Alan Greenspan (below), and its vice chairman is the president of
the New York Fed. Traditionally, the regional Fed presidents are viewed as
more hawkish on inflation than the governors, but they are also in closer
contact with the business community in their districts, from whom they are
hearing plenty of reasons why not to raise interest rates.
How do they decide?
Like other central banks, the Fed once used the growth of the money supply
as a target, but changes in the structure of the economy mean that monetary
measures like M1 and M2 no longer have any demonstrable use as a predictor
of inflation. Inflation measures, such as the consumer price index, tell you
more about the past than the future, and also overstate the pace of
inflation, many Fed economists argue. Now, the FOMC basically makes a
forecast of where it thinks the economy is heading, using a wide and
shifting range of indicators such as credit market developments,
manufacturers' order books and lead times, and tightens or loosens its
policy accordingly. One critical element is what Fed officials call the
'loss factor' - how easily can they undo the damage if their forecast turns
out to be wrong? That argues for a series of smaller interest rate increases
rather than one sharp yank on the monetary rope.
How does the Fed move interest rates?
To raise interest rates, the Fed operates in the credit market to take cash
out of the system by selling government securities to the banks. It would
undertake a reserve repurchase, selling government securities to the money
market for a fixed period, usually one day, with an agreement to buy them
back at a fixed interest rate. By reducing the amount of money available,
this raises the interest rate banks can charge for the reserves they hold at
the Federal Reserve and lend each other overnight - the federal funds rate,
which currently stands at 4.75 per cent. The Fed can also raise the discount
rate, currently 4 per cent, which it charges when banks borrow directly from
its discount window - designed to operate mostly as a lender of last resort.
So what exactly is going to happen tomorrow?
Of the 39 banks which operate as primary dealers in the government
securities market, 34 are predicting an increase of half a percentage point,
or 50 basis points in the language used by bond traders, lifting the federal
funds rate to 5.25 per cent. Only one dealer is predicting no change,
according to a survey by Dow Jones Capital Markets, while four banks expect
an increase of three quarters of a percentage point. Almost everyone in the
financial markets would like a move of more than half a percentage point - a
view not shared by business. Most dealers think the Fed has been 'behind the
curve' in not acting sooner to cool the rapid growth of the third quarter.
The markets could be placated if the Fed raises the discount rate by more
than the federal funds rate, or issues a tough statement on its
determination to keep inflation under control.
When will we know?
In the past, the FOMC has not made its actions known immediately. It gave
the Fed chairman his orders, but left him to act in the open markets between
FOMC meetings. This year, however, the FOMC has announced all its interest
rate moves, and even given a brief explanation, usually around lunchtime,
Washington time.
</TEXT>
<XX>
