<HEADLINE>
FT  14 NOV 94 / This Week: Film/Video
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIGEL ANDREWS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Environmental soundness has come to cinema in recent years. When in doubt,
recycle. This week should have seen the opening in London of Natural Born
Killers, but the censor decided it was too mad, bad, violent and new.
So we have revivals of My Fair Lady (no serial murders) and Bicycle Thieves
(non-violent vehicle robbery), plus a lavish, no-brain Hollywood adventure
drawn from a 1930s radio serial: The Shadow has Alec Baldwin prowling
through New York in a hat and cape, righting wrongs and fighting wicked
Orientals. Racist subtext? Never mind. At least there is no real blood or
real emotion being spilled over your popcorn.
On video, too, Aunt Edna may breathe freely in the run-up to Christmas. We
have a mixture of innocent fun - Cool Runnings, with its comedy re-enactment
of the Jamaican bobsleigh team's glory week at the 1988 Olympics - and
erratic attempts at grown-up entertainment.
The Paper, starring Michael Keaton and Glenn Close, is a brisk, caustic
newspaper yarn after The Front Page. And Ken Loach's blithe comedy of
working-class doldrums, Raining Stones, comes to the retail shelves.
If you fancy a movie of that hit stage play about transvestite passion, M.
Butterfly, you may not fancy it after seeing David Cronenberg's version.
John Lone - mascara, kimono and rugger-player shoulders - makes a less than
convincing woman, and Jeremy Irons as the love-struck consul fades into the
cod-Chinese scenery.
The best place to be is once more the London Film Festival. The final week
offers you two curious and wonderful tales of sex and soul-searching. From
Canada, Atom Egoyan's Exotica (Wednesday) is a mazy mind-melodrama, shot in
a nightclub resembling a human aquarium. And from Taiwan, Tsai Ming-liang's
Vive L'Amour, the 1994 Venice Golden Lion winner, maroons two youths and a
girl in an untenanted apartment and watches their fantasies singly and
collectively explode.
Dangerous and original movies. Happily, the censor exercises no sway over
the LFF. So for two precious weeks each year grown-up moviegoers have a
place to go and be grown-up.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
