<PROFILE>_AN-EKNDLABZFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941114
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  14 NOV 94 / This Week: Time to knock out the gentlemen - Sport
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN WHEATLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Boxing desperately awaits the second coming. Next spring, prisoner No 922335
leaves the Indiana Youth Detention Centre: Mike Tyson will be back on the
street and quickly into the ring.
'I'm sure he'll fight within six to eight weeks of getting out,' predicts
Frank Warren, the London fight promoter. 'He's below his fighting weight, in
the gym every day, and his attitude is good.' When Warren tells you that
Tyson's return to the ring is going to be a mega-industry and that his
comeback fight could gross Dollars 100m on pay-per-view TV alone, it is
probably best to ignore the numbers.
Warren does, after all, have the UK TV rights to shift, and is a consummate
salesman. He is also honest and intelligent enough to admit that boxing at
present has a massive credibility problem.
George Foreman, a sweating, heaving, 46-year-old tub of lard, is
re-annointed world heavyweight champion in Las Vegas. In Hong Kong,
promoters wrangle, boxers such as Frank Bruno stand idle, and a whole show
goes down for lack of honest interest. Most bizarre of all, Chris Eubank,
dressed like a character in an Ealing comedy, struts around the world
fighting no-hopers and telling the tiny crowds they will be seeing nothing
special since he hates to fight.
His manager, Barry Hearn, an accountant turned snooker impresario, has sold
Eubank's 10-fight sequence to Sky TV for Pounds 10m. So far the broadcaster
has received only poor ratings and ridicule. 'It's a joke. Hearn took Kelvin
McKenzie for a well-deserved ride. Pounds 10m quid down the drain,' laughs
Warren. McKenzie was briefly joint head of BSkyB after leaving the
editorship of The Sun. But Warren hates the damage this kind of fiasco does
to a sport that is also a way of life. 'Eubank thinks he's clever to knock
boxing, thinks it's what the public want to hear. But look at Gerald Ratner.
He lost his money, his job, his family company just by insulting the
customer. It's no different to Eubank telling the crowd he's going to give
them a crap fight.'
I went to see Warren to test a theory that boxing's real problem is not the
sportsmen but the dilettante promoters who are taking it over, drawn by the
potent mixture of blood and money. The notion came to me when I saw film
producer John Daly (The Last Emperor and Platoon) trying to patch up the
Hong Kong show he'd dreamt up. It became a nightmare. Not a punch was thrown
(at least not in the ring).
'It's Vietnam here,' said a distraught Daly in the colony's Ritz Carlton
Hotel, under siege from creditors, hoteliers and fighters. 'Basically, I
just want to get out alive.' Five years ago I met Daly in Hollywood. The
Oscar for Last Emperor sat on his desk. We drove to the Polo Lounge in his
Mercedes sports soft-top and it was all 'Hi John' from the stars at lesser
tables. But what he really wanted to talk about wasn't movies but Ali v
Foreman in Zaire, 15 years earlier.
Daly had been a player in the 'Rumble in the Jungle' promotion, and he
always remembered it. Daly's partner in the Hong King venture was American
promoter Bob Arum, a Harvard lawyer who was once an adviser to the Kennedys,
was sent in to investigate boxing - and became a player.
In contrast to the respectability of Arum is the fear and loathing with
which Don King is regarded - mistakely, says Warren, who often acts as the
Harlem preacher's London connection. 'If Don had run that fiasco in Hong
Kong he'd have been crucified by the media, yet the Hollywood guys, the
lawyers and the accountants, weaselled their way out of it, keeping their
so-called integrity.'
Unsettling those around him is undoubtedly part of King's business
technique, along with the flamboyant hair and the costumes. In Kinshasa he
turned up at the 1974 fight in African robes. 'If King put on a show in
Alaska, he'd turn out with a sleigh and dogs,' said one observer at the
Foreman comeback fight.
Yet King delivers, for the audience and the boxers. 'Don's an easy target,'
says Warren. 'He's black, he's loud, he's been to prison. But I'll bet he's
made more black millionaires than anybody else in sport.' King also has a
terrific grasp of the big picture, which the clowning often obscures.
Between 1987 and 1992, when King virtually ran the big-time heavyweight
division, there was a unified championship. Tyson was The Man. Since then it
has fragmented into three different titles (four if one counts the peculiar
WBO title).
Lennox Lewis came as near as anyone this century to providing Britain with
an undisputed world heavyweight champion. His talent was never in doubt. But
American connections like Dan Duva and a London promoter who had never been
to a boxing match until three years ago, combined in a bonfire of naivety to
prevent Lewis unifying the title. Following his knock-out by Oliver McCall
two months ago, he may never get the chance.
Six months from now, boxing will probably be very different to the muddled,
laughable scene we have now. Tyson faces no worthwhile opposition, and King
and Warren will cut bigger deals on his success and celebrity than every
before. 'We're going to keep the accountants and dabblers out of this,'
promised Warren.
It is time for the gentlemen to get out of the players' way.
</TEXT>
