<HEADLINE>
FT  14 NOV 94 / Eurotram unveiled
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ABB Transportation, Britain's largest train maker, has unveiled the
Eurotram, which project manager John Swanson and marketing manager John
Clark hope will provide the company with significant orders to replace
diminishing train business, Chris Tighe writes.
A Pounds 50m order for 26 Eurotrams is nearing completion at ABB's York
works for the French city of Strasbourg, where a new tram service will be
inaugurated next week.
The sleek, glass-fronted vehicle, painted cream and green with a pastel
interior, is the first tram to be made at the York works in its 150-year
history. Securing more train or tram orders in the near future is crucial
for the works. Its orders run out next October when it finishes its last
British Rail order, worth Pounds 150m, for 188 Networker commuter trains.
The imminent completion of the Strasbourg tram order led to the announcement
in September of 289 redundancies, a quarter of the workforce. The jobs will
go by the end of this year.
ABB believes the electrically powered Eurotram offers it a potentially
important market opportunity in Britain and continental Europe.
