<HEADLINE>
FT  14 NOV 94 / Hospital chief slapped down: Bottomley disowns claim that
patients should be third in doctors' priorities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mrs Virginia Bottomley, the health secretary, and health service
professional organisations yesterday disowned comments by a hospital trust
chairman that patients should come third on the list of doctors' priorities,
after the relationship with their managers and their own professional
development.
Mr Roy Lilley, chairman of the Homewood NHS Trust in Chertsey, Surrey, set
out the priorities in an article which has yet to be published in the
journal HealthCare Today.
Department of Health officials said Mr Lilley was 'speaking of his own
volition and not for the secretary of state'. Patients had always been put
first and this principle applied throughout the health service, the
department said.
The National Association of Health Authorities and Trusts said the paramount
duty of doctors should be to patients and described Mr Lilley's remarks as
'not particularly helpful'.
Mr Lilley said yesterday that he never said that patients should come last:
'Patients are at the very centre of everything we do but, first of all,
doctors have got to get the relationships with the organisations they work
with sorted out.'
Mr Lilley said Mrs Bottomley expected everybody in the health service to put
patients first, but 'down here, at the coal face, there are some real
difficulties with working relationships with doctors'.
After their organisations, doctors have a duty to themselves and their
professional training, Mr Lilley said. He claimed that supermarket cashiers
received more rigorous training in the latest technologies than doctors were
likely to get in developments in medical techniques.
He added: 'As it stands at the moment, a doctor who fancies having a go at
something can, out of curiosity, go and get himself involved in a branch of
medicine or surgery without having to get more qualifications.' This
contrasted with, for example, airline pilots, who had annual medical checks
and regular training.
'Even the little girl on the checkout in Sainsbury's, if they introduce a
new till, has to go on a course to find out how to use it,' he said.
To meet Treasury requirements, performance management had to be introduced
into trusts by next March, Mr Lilley said. But the British Medical
Association had opposed the move and 'just waved two fingers at everybody
and that's made the relationships that managers have with doctors very
difficult indeed'.
Mr Lilley said patients could be better cared for 'if you've got an
organisation that isn't in chaos and if procedures are being carried out by
people who are well-trained and up to date. That seems to me to be
straightforward logic.'
Mr Philip Hunt, director of the trusts association, said the key to
improving the NHS was for doctors and managers to work in partnership. 'If
you come out with statements about how awful doctors are you are going to
undermine that partnership,' he said.
The British Medical Association, which represents doctors, said Mr Lilley's
views were 'completely outrageous'. Patients' interests had to come first.
</TEXT>
