<HEADLINE>
FT  14 NOV 94 / Call for greater quango scrutiny
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A former Conservative MP today adds his voice to mounting calls for more
effective scrutiny of quangos.
In a study published by the free-market Adam Smith Institute, Sir Philip
Holland, former MP for Carlton and an ex-ministerial aide, argues that
quangos - quasi-autonomous non-governmental organisations - should face
automatic extinction unless MPs vote to renew them.
Identifying more than 2,000 quangos - down from 3,068 in 1979 - Sir Philip
calls for legislation forcing such bodies to 'come back to parliament every
few years . . . for a renewed lease on life'.
'Unless parliament specifically votes for each one to continue, they will be
terminated,' he suggests.
Sir Philip calls for the membership and accounts of all quangos to be placed
on an open public register. This would disclose the names of all appointees
and give details of how much they were paid, what work was undertaken and
what action was taken by ministers as a result.
But he argues that National Health Service hospital trusts and
grant-maintained schools should not be 'hunted as quangos'.
The Hunting of the Quango. Adam Smith Institute, 23 Great Smith Street,
London SW1P 2BL. Pounds 24.
</TEXT>
