<HEADLINE>
FT  14 NOV 94 / Clearing a path to the facts: How to avoid being fobbed off
when seeking access to official information
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM LEWIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
One of Whitehall's best kept secrets over the past seven months has been the
government's guidelines on access to official information.
Launched in April amid claims that it would open up to the public previously
secret documents and research, the Code of Practice on Access to Government
Information has so far proved to be a damp squib. Figures on how many
requests have been made under the code are not yet available but officials
believe the number is tiny.
Most of the publicity the code has received has been negative. Last week,
for example, the Campaign for Freedom of Information released details of a
survey which found that some departments are demanding money up-front before
they even agree to handle inquiries.
In spite of this Mr Maurice Frankel, director of the campaign, wants to
encourage wider use of the code. He said: 'Try not to be put off by the
charges as they can be appealed against.'
Mr Frankel argues that though the code has obvious flaws, the presence of a
referee - the Parliamentary Ombudsman - to rule on disputes between
individuals and civil servants is a big step forward.
Below is the Financial Times's seven-point guide for businesses and
individuals wanting to make the best use of the code:
1. Starting out
Get a list of the departments and quangos covered by the code, contact names
and addresses, and a copy of the code by telephoning 0345 223242, or by
writing to Open Government, Room 417b, Office of Public Service and Science,
70 Whitehall, London, SW1A 2AS.
Also request a copy of the detailed guidance on the code the cabinet office
has produced for other government departments. This is called Guidance on
Interpretation.
Departments are likely to send you an application form on which to make your
request. Ask for a copy of the department's guidelines for dealing with
requests under the code, including charging.
2. Charges
You may be charged a fee before your request is even looked at. For example,
the Foreign Office will demand a Pounds 15 non-refundable fee which must be
sent in with the request.
However, certain types of request must be granted free, such as those
relating to social security benefits and government grants, and you will
always be told of the charges in advance and asked if you will agree to
them. Ultimately you can appeal to Mr William Reid, the Parliamentary
Ombudsman, via an MP, against any unreasonable fees.
3. Penning the request
If it is not already stated on the department form, add to the top of it:
'This is a request under the Code of Practice on Access to Government
Information.' This will ensure that you are able to appeal to the Ombudsman
later. Also ask for the information to be supplied 'within 20 days as
required by the Code'.
4. What to ask for
Make your request as specific as possible to reduce the chances of your
request being turned down. Information available under the code is meant to
be in the form of summaries of government documents. However if you want to
see a particular report which you know exists, try asking for it.
If you do not have any specific documents in mind, ask for a list of all the
relevant reports and records which the department holds relating to the
issue which interests you.
When the government announces a new policy or decision ask for the 'facts
and analysis' behind the decision, as this information has to be provided
under the code.
5. Personal Files
Officials believe that most requests by individuals will relate to personal
files held by government departments and quangos. You should be able to
obtain non-computerised files under the code, but will still face
restrictions on accessing pre-1991 medical records.
The government has said it intends to create a new legal right of access to
non-computerised files, thus bolstering rights of access under the code, but
no timetable for legislation has been announced.
6. Following up
Challenge any refusal. This may apply when you have been denied access to a
particular document or when you believe you have not been given a full and
accurate summary of a report. Insist on being told which of the code's
exemptions has been used.
You can then go for a departmental appeal. This will involve an inquiry by
another civil servant checking your case and will cost nothing.
Try arguing that disclosure should be made in 'the public interest', as the
code allows.
7. Complaints to the Ombudsman
If you are not satisfied by the departmental appeal you can appeal to the
Parliamentary Ombudsman through any MP.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9199 General Government, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 9
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT944-9870</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EKNDLABKFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941114
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  14 NOV 94 / BNFL plans to sell off precision work business
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Nuclear Fuels is planning to sell off some of its specialised
high-precision manufacturing expertise within the next three years.
It is currently exploiting this expertise to build new markets in the
pharmaceutical, chemical and aerospace industries. However, it plans to sell
this new business to its management once commercial viability is
established.
The new business will use techniques developed at Capenhurst, BNFL's
engineering factory in the Wirral, to make components and vessels for its
reprocessing plant at Sellafield.
The techniques enable drums and containers to be mass-produced out of
inch-thick stainless steel to an accuracy of three microns or three
millionths of a metre - smaller than a particle of dust. Such accuracy is
needed for nuclear safety.
In an effort to secure non-nuclear spin-offs by transferring the
manufacturing technology to products for other industries, state-owned BNFL
has formed a wholly owned subsidiary called Deva Manufacturing Services and
equipped it with Pounds 5m of computer-controlled and robotic machine tools
on an industrial estate near Chester.
Its first 30 employees are skilled Capenhurst workers who would have been
made redundant following BNFL's rundown of activities now that Thorp, its
thermal oxide reprocessing plant at Sellafield, has been completed.
Deva's first contract is worth Pounds 50m over 10 years, making steel drums
for storing intermediate-level nuclear waste. It plans to double turnover by
selling high-precision steel products to the chemical and pharmaceutical
industries.
The company believes it will be able to exploit its ability to manufacture
to tight tolerances. Industries moving to robotic production methods require
vessels to fit exactly between robotic arms or automatic handling machinery.
The nuclear storage drums cost about Pounds 1,800 each. Deva will also
develop its own brand of a cheaper, re-useable stainless steel drum in the
Pounds 250-Pounds 400 price range for the pharmaceutical industry.
Mr Neville Chamberlain, BNFL's chief executive, said Deva's management would
be encouraged to bid to buy the business out once it was established.
</TEXT>
