<HEADLINE>
FT  14 NOV 94 / Magnet advisers to settle cases
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT CORZINE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Advisers and bankers to the failed management buy-out of Magnet, the
retailer of fitted kitchens, have agreed to settle court cases in which
damages could have been as high as Pounds 1bn.
Parties involved include Bankers Trust, the US bank which led the banking
syndicate, GE Capital, one of the syndicate's members, Arthur Andersen,
adviser to Magnet's management, and Arthur Young, Magnet's auditor.
All parties to the dispute have signed a settlement agreement that will come
into effect when one undisclosed condition is met. Those close to the
dispute say a full settlement could be in place by the end of the month.
The case involved two separate legal actions. GE Capital, which lost about
Pounds 70m, claimed damages from Bankers Trust, which in turn sued
accountants Arthur Andersen for Pounds 600m. That is roughly the amount lost
by the banks which backed the deal.
The companies involved refuse to discuss the settlement terms. But the
payment expected to be made by Arthur Andersen to Bankers Trust is thought
to be less than Pounds 50m. Arthur Young, now part of Ernst &amp; Young, is
expected to contribute to the settlement.
Bankers Trust argued that Arthur Andersen was negligent for failing to
provide it with an objective and independent report on Magnet.
The accounting firm denied the allegation. It claimed that it never did any
due diligence or audit work for the bank, and that its duty during the
buy-out was entirely to Magnet management.
GE Capital claimed that Bankers Trust had 'completely failed' to discharge
its responsibilities as syndicate leader and ignored warnings about Magnet's
financial health.
The Pounds 629m Magnet buy-out in 1989 was the largest ever and the first
involving 'mezzanine' finance. Senior lenders, led by Bankers Trust, put in
Pounds 372.5m. Refinancing talks between Magnet and the banks began after
the deal closed, and substantial interest on the debt was rolled-up into the
capital.
Lower-than-expected profits, the collapse of the housing market and high
interest rates soon took their toll on the highly-borrowed retailer.
Airedale Holdings, Magnet's parent company, had debts of Pounds 800m by the
time it went into receivership in December 1992.
The banks that were the original senior lenders bought the operating company
from the receiver. It was sold earlier this year for Pounds 56m.
The court cases had been expected to raise a series of important legal
precedents about the nature of diligence on acquisitions, and the duty of
care of corporate finance advisers and lead banks to syndicate members.
</TEXT>
