<HEADLINE>
FT  14 NOV 94 / Concern at loss of building recruits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MOTOKO RICH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The construction industry is losing most of the recruits it would once have
had because of the expansion of full-time education, says Sir Clifford
Chetwood, chairman of the Construction Industry Training Board.
As the CITB, one of two remaining statutory training boards, prepared to
unveil a new training strategy today, Sir Clifford said: 'Eighty per cent of
the young people that we normally would have had access to for our
apprenticeships are now following a full-time education until 17 or 18.'
Sir Clifford, who began his career as a trainee building manager, said it
was important for the board to adjust its training schemes 'so that we do
not lose access to the non-academic element of the 80 per cent'.
He added: 'A lot of them will probably find out after a year that they are
not suited academically and will seek to resort to a trade involving
physical skills.'
When asked if the industry would simply lose many of those who continue
their education to other careers, he said: 'You would have to have the IQ.
There are a vast number of people out there who are only semi-literate. We
will always be dealing with these people. And when they are non-academic
they are extremely well co-ordinated.'
</TEXT>
