<HEADLINE>
FT  14 NOV 94 / Taipei may ease market curbs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA TYSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TAIPEI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Taiwan is considering relaxation of curbs on foreign investment in the
domestic stock market, in moves apparently timed to boost share prices just
before the elections on December 3. Officials from the Finance Ministry,
central bank, Economics Ministry and Planning Ministry are to meet this
month to decide whether to raise or remove ceilings on foreign investment in
listed shares, the Economic Daily News reported yesterday. Securities
authorities have proposed lifting limits except for companies involved in
cement, inland transportation, finance, commercial paper and natural gas.
Government-approved foreign institutional investors today may not
individually buy more than 5 per cent of the listed shares in a single stock
or more than 10 per cent collectively. Foreign individuals may not to buy
Taiwan shares. There is a ceiling of USDollars 7.5bn (Pounds 4.6bn) on
foreign funds which may be remitted to the country to invest in domestic
shares, representing about 4 per cent of market capitalisation. Each foreign
institution may invest a maximum of Dollars 200m.
