<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 94 / National Theatre may make a loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The National Theatre warned yesterday that it might make a loss this year
after reporting a surplus of Pounds 539,000 on a turnover of Pounds 28.3m in
1993-94. The Royal Shakespeare Company, the UK's other leading publicly
funded theatre company, reported a surplus of almost Pounds 1.4m last year
on a Pounds 27.4m turnover.
The hot summer and the failure of some new productions, notably Johnny on
the Spot, hit box office income at the National Theatre, with seat occupancy
down on the 77 per cent achieved in 1993-94. It is returning its popular
success, The Wind in the Willows, to the repertoire in the next few weeks
which should help to keep any deficit below Pounds 500,000.
The National Theatre has been successful in controlling costs in recent
years, and has accumulated a reserve of Pounds 927,000. In contrast, the RSC
still has a deficit - of just over Pounds 1m - but for the third successive
year it has managed to cut it.
Both companies are suffering from the freeze in government subsidy, which
accounts for just over 40 per cent of their incomes. The National Theatre
received Pounds 12m from the Arts Council in 1993-94, but, like the RSC, has
been allocated a standstill grant in 1994-95, equivalent to a 2.5 per cent
loss in income. The RSC received Pounds 8.47m from the council, but is also
supported by the Corporation of London.
</TEXT>
