<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 94 / Weekend Money: Finance week
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
BUSINESS
Bill Clinton answered the US Republican party's sweeping mid-term election
triumph by promising to block opposition attempts to 'turn the clock back'
to the economic policies of the 1980s.
John Major won cabinet backing for public spending cuts of between Pounds
4bn and Pounds 5bn in this month's Budget. The details were agreed after
ministers accepted compromise proposals for cuts to the Pounds 8bn housing
benefit budget.
The UK government is expected to revise upwards its estimate of
third-quarter economic growth after official figures showed industrial
production grew unexpectedly strongly in the three months to September.
Businesses are not investing enough because they expect too great a return
on their investments, Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary,
told the CBI's annual conference.
Lloyd's of London gave the go-ahead for individual members of the market to
make a switch away from underwriting insurance policies on the basis of
unlimited liability.
A group of investment banks and former professional advisers to pension
schemes controlled by the late Robert Maxwell offered to pay between Pounds
200m and Pounds 300m in a 'global settlement' of all outstanding claims.
Norwich Union, one of the UK's largest insurers, announced plans to shed up
to 2,000 jobs - a fifth of its workforce - over five years.
Non-executive directors of the Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester Building Society are
to be urged by some of the society's members to think again about the
board's agreement to the Lloyds Bank Pounds 1.8bn cash offer.
The Treasury set out part of the regulatory framework it intends to put in
place for open-ended investment companies when they are allowed in the UK
next year.
David Sieff, chairman of the National Lottery Charities Board, admitted the
board, which could have Pounds 100m a year to distribute to charities, might
not start making grants until late next year.
COMPANIES
The cost of cutting prices and jobs held back revenues and profitability at
British Telecommunications in the first six months of the year.
TeleWest, the largest UK cable operator, pushed ahead with flotation plans
with a pathfinder prospectus suggesting a total value for the company of
between Pounds 1.25bn and Pounds 1.45bn.
British Sky Broadcasting, the satellite television venture, is pushing ahead
with a December flotation in London and New York, expected to value the
company at between Pounds 4bn and Pounds 4.5bn.
Anglian Water announced a 20 per cent rise in pre-tax profits to Pounds
120.6m for the half-year to September 30 and declared a 9.6 per cent
increase in its interim dividend from 7.3p to 8p.
North West Water announced a wide-ranging review review of its activities,
which will mean continued job losses.
The Prudential Corporation, the UK's largest investing institution, is
poised to follow the trend of other large companies and cut the length of
its directors' service contracts.
Burton, the clothing retail group that includes Debenhams, Burtons and
Dorothy Perkins, more than doubled profits last year despite falling into
the red in its multiples division.
Production losses from the recent oil strike in Nigeria, and tighter
refining margins in Asia, caused third-quarter profits for the Royal
Dutch/Shell group to ease back 1 per cent to Pounds 853m.
Royal Insurance, the composite insurer, forecast a 10 per cent reduction in
its UK workforce over the next three years in spite of a near-tripling of
pre-tax profits in the first nine months to Pounds 311m.
Commercial Union, another composite insurer, reported pre-tax profits up
Pounds 165m at Pounds 305m for the first nine months.
Amstrad launched a scheme to allow consumers to buy its personal computers
and faxes direct from the company through Amstrad Business Direct.
Marks and Spencer, the UK's most profitable retailer, lifted interim profits
by 15 per cent on the back of a 7 per cent increase in sales. It lifted
continental European sales by 20 per cent.
Cable &amp; Wireless, the UK telecommunications group, announced a 'substantial
cost and head-count reduction programme' at its UK-based Mercury
Communications subsidiary while reporting an 11 per cent rise in interim
pre-tax profits.
A 7 per cent increase in airline passengers helped to fuel a Pounds 28m rise
in pre-tax profits, to Pounds 265m, at privatised airports group BAA during
the six months ended September.
Forget soap wars - the latest battle is for babies' bottoms. Procter &amp;
Gamble, which produces Pampers, complained to the Advertising Standards
Authority about magazine adverts by nappy rival Kimberly-Clark, which makes
Huggies.
Gartmore, the UK fund manager, formed a joint venture with NationsBank,
America's third-biggest bank, which will allow it to sell international fund
management expertise to US retail and pension fund investors.
British Airways announced record second-quarter profits and an 'encouraging'
outlook for the full year, as it reaped the rewards of a campaign to win
business travellers and tighten cost controls. The figures were above
expectations, and lifted BA shares.
SG Warburg, the UK-based investment bank, said it would review staff levels
and delay planned investments as part of a drive to cut costs after losing
money on trading.
Sony Electronic Publishing is to open a base in Liverpool as its European
centre for design and development of computer and video games, creating 259
jobs.
Henderson Administration, the fund management group, increased pre-tax
profits by 22 per cent to Pounds 11.2m for the six months to September 30,
compared with Pounds 9.2m last time.
MARKETS
The dollar rallied initially on foreign exchanges after the US mid-term
elections, but Wall Street retreated after early gains amid concerns the
result would undermine investor confidence.
After a sluggish start to the week, the FT-SE 100 index rose - due partly to
the US election. It broke the 3,100 level by Thursday's close, but retreated
on Friday.
Broadly-based selling in Tokyo depressed equities on Thursday as a decline
in speculative stocks and privatised issues prompted arbitrage-linked sales.
The Nikkei 225 average ended 159.03 lower at 19,264.85.
UK utility stocks moved against a strong market trend on Wednesday after
Labour's shadow chancellor, Gordon Brown, called for a one-off windfall tax
on the 'excess profits' of the privatised utility companies.
Two newcomers to the stock market, TLG, formerly the lighting division of
Thorn EMI, and Tele-Cine made reasonably successful debuts on Thursday, both
moving to modest premiums over their issue prices.
Shares in Coal Investments, the mining company, lost another 7 per cent of
their value on Wednesday after the company reported a 10-week delay in its
mine re-opening programme and interim pre-tax losses of Pounds 10.2m.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
