<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 94 / Food &amp; Drink: Bells starts to trade up - Appetisers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILES MACDONOGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
What do you do when you are a whisky company faced with a decline in whisky
consumption as well as a disaffection among the younger drinkers in favour
of Bourbon and vodka?
If you are Bells you trade up. Instead of the old five-year-old Bells whisky
the stuff in the bottle is now eight years old. What is more, the price
remains the same.
With nearly half the malt whisky distilleries in its portfolio, United
Distillers certainly has the wherewithal to make a great blended whisky.
The percentage of malt in the new Bells has not changed. The company says,
simply, that it has altered the 'balance'. Still, about 60 per cent of the
whisky is grain from the UP Cameronbridge distillery.
The main malts are Glenkinchie, Blair Atholl, Dufftown, Linkwood, Inchgower,
Oban and Caol Ila. Both the Dufftown and a percentage of the Linkwood have a
heavy sherry treatment. The sherry shows on the new Bells. Whereas the old
'tinker' had a slightly disagreeable rancid character, the new Bells has a
more finely-tuned toffee and raisins flavour from the sherry.
Now that most of the large cognac houses seem to have abandoned the UK for
the more profitable far eastern market, it is a rare pleasure to see someone
still actively selling cognac and good cognac too.
Delamain cognacs come from Jarnac on the Charente. The family can trace its
participation in the brandy business back to the eary 17th century and is
the last privately-owned merchant house in the region, with Alain Braastad
at the helm, on his mother's side a direct descendant of the founders of the
house.
Delamain is special in that it sells only Grande Champagne cognacs which are
25-years-old and over. This means that all their brandies have that rancio
character: the aromas of rich fruitcake.
Pale and Dry is an average of 25 years, a cognac of great breeding and
delicacy. Many prefer it to the more expensive Vesper which averages 35
years and is a heavier, woodier cognac. The oldest commercially available is
the Tres Venerable, which is between 50 and 60 years old. (At around 60
years cognac is normally removed from casks to prevent it from becoming too
woody.) This cognac has a persistence on the palate which lingers for
minutes.
It is worth shopping around for Pale and Dry as there are considerable
variations in price: La Reserve, 56 Walton Street, London SW3. (071-589
2020), Pounds 45; Selfridges (071-629 1234) Pounds 42.50; Reid Wines, The
Mill, Hallatrow Bristol (01761-452645) Pounds 35; and Lea and Sandeman, 301
Fulham Road, SW10 and 211 Kensington Church Street, W8 (071-376 4767) Pounds
36.50. Lea and Sandeman also stocks Vesper at Pounds 49 and Tres Venerable
at Pounds 98.99.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2085 Distilled and Blended Liquors.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
