<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 94 / Weekend Money (Financial Planning): Feedback . . . -
Briefcase
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From JH ALKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
I read with great interest the article in the Weekend FT (November 5) by
Kevin Goldstein-Jackson headlined: 'The wrong policies'. I agree entirely
that 'people should be encouraged to create and manage their own pension
fund, rather than having to invest through an institution'. I would,
however, prefer this to apply to Peps.
These were introduced as an incentive to the private investor to save and
invest in the stock market. But the only real winners have been fund
managers and brokers whose income has been increased through the purchase
and ongoing management charges of Peps.
I feel that to encourage people to manage their own personal pension fund
would be too politically sensitive because, if it failed, the individual
might become reliant on state benefits (ie, income support, housing benefit,
etc.). But this should not be the case with Peps, as their pension should
still be available.
I appreciate that this would not have the same impact on the balance of
shareholder power. But if more people were attracted to Peps, it would be a
step in the right direction to increasing that power.
JH Alker,
Newark, Notts
