<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 94 / Weekend Money (Financial Planning): Verbal, but is it
binding? - Briefcase
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Three years ago, I bought shares in the private company for which I was then
working. At the time, I was told I could not sell them without board
approval. Later, I was informed that, if I found a buyer, I would have to
offer them first at the same price to other shareholders. But since I did
not sign any document/s, am I bound to do any of this?
Verbal agreements are enforceable, so the fact that you did not actually
sign any document/s may not necessarily be relied upon. In any case, other
shareholders may well give you a better price for your shares. (Murray
Johnstone).
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All inquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
