<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 94 / Weekend Money (Financial Planning): Minimising tax liability
 -Briefcase
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
I will lose my job at the end of the year and do not expect to work again
but my wife will continue to do so. Her salary is around Pounds 60,000 and
we have Pounds 200,000 of investments held in joint names. Can we change
these investments to my name only to minimise tax liability? And could we
reverse the process in the future to maximise capital gains tax exemption?
As a general principle, we do not recommend that married women hand all
their investments over to their husbands absolutely. In any case, the fact
that re-transfer is contemplated in the future would defeat your tax
avoidance scheme because half the income would be deemed still to be your
wife's (by virtue of section 674A of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act
1988).
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All inquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
</TEXT>
