<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 94 / Weekend Money (Companies): British Steel forges on - The
week ahead
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MONDAY: British Steel's interim pre-tax profits are thought to have leapt to
between Pounds 130m and Pounds 150m, compared with Pounds 27m a year ago.
The company, which dominates the UK steel market, is benefiting from price
increases, supply shortages and better demand as the UK manufacturing sector
recovers from recession.
TUESDAY: Full-year pre-tax profits from industrial gases company BOC are
estimated at about Pounds 260m, down sharply on last year thanks to an
Pounds 85m restructuring provision. Interest will centre on underlying
growth in the health-care business, which has been hit by the US expiry of
the patent on the anaesthetic gas Forane, and on how much BOC has benefited
from the wider upturn in chemicals sales and prices.
TUESDAY: Results for the first nine months of 1994 from General Accident,
the composite insurer, are expected to show pre-tax profits of about Pounds
330m, against Pounds 206m last time, highlighting the buoyancy of the UK
insurance sector.
Attention could focus on the group's assessment of likely trends in premium
rates, which will influence future profitability.
TUESDAY: Insurance broker Sedgwick is expected to report an increase in
pre-tax profits to about Pounds 75m from Pounds 64m in the first nine months
of 1993.
TUESDAY/THURSDAY: The stock market will be anxious for signals that rents
are rising and occupiers are taking additional space when Great Portland
Estates and Land Securities - which together make up almost one-third of
quoted property sector, report interim results.
Neither company revalues its property portfolio at the half-year stage but,
for property values to increase in the long term, it is necessary for rents
to rise. Unless investors see signs of stronger demand for business space,
property shares will remain in the doldrums.
Great Portland, which cut its dividend in June for the first time in its
35-year history, is expected to show a marked improvement over last year's
Pounds 40m rental income when it announces interim figures on Tuesday.
Analysts expect pre-tax profit of around Pounds 17.6m, against Pounds 16m.
As the UK's largest quoted property company, Land Securities' figures on
Thursday will be especially important for sentiment. In the first half of
last year, the company reported rental income of Pounds 192m and pre-tax
profits of Pounds 118.9m, including a contribution from sales of investment
property. Analysts are looking for pre-tax profits of about Pounds 118m this
time.
TUESDAY/THURSDAY: The two main electricity generators in England and Wales
report next week amid expectations that they will provide generous dividend
increases to shareholders. Analysts believe that both PowerGen, which
reports on Tuesday, and National Power, which reports on Thursday, are
capable of lifting pay-outs by at least 16 per cent. Some have pencilled in
more than 20 per cent. The results are the last before the government sells
off its remaining 40 per cent stakes in the companies in February.
WEDNESDAY: British Gas's third-quarter results usually show a loss for the
quarter, which covers the months of lowest demand. Analysts expect losses in
the range of Pounds 200m-240m. The results coincide with the Queen's Speech,
in which the government is expected to announce new legislation to break up
 -in 1998 - British Gas's monopoly over 18m residential customers.
WEDNESDAY: Vosper Thornycroft, the Southampton-based shipbuilding and
engineering group, is expected to report interim pre-tax profits of just
over Pounds 10m, compared with Pounds 9.08m last time. Analysts will seek
news of a possible Kuwaiti contract to build up to eight fast patrol boats.
The order was reported recently to have gone to CMN of France, but the UK
group is not giving up until the deal has been signed definitely.
WEDNESDAY: Unigate, the food and distribution group, is expected to report
flat interim profits of around Pounds 50m following tough trading in the
grocery sector and deregulation of the milk market. This month, the group,
which delivers milk to 1.6m households in south and south-west England,
raised its prices by 2p a pint to 40p.
THURSDAY: Whitbread opens the brewers' reporting season with interims that
should benefit from good summer weather, particularly in the south of
England where it is strongest. But pressure remains on beer margins and it
will also be affected by the lack of dividends from the Whitbread Investment
Company, which has been wound up. Pre-tax profits of around Pounds 138m,
against Pounds 132.3, are forecast.
THURSDAY: FKI, the electrical engineering group, is expected to report
interims of about Pounds 30m, compared with Pounds 22m last time. Having
abandoned a Pounds 400m US purchase in May because of the fall in London
share prices, the Halifax-based company will be quizzed about its
acquisition intentions.
THURSDAY: Willis Corroon, the insurance broker, is expected to show a fall
in pre-tax profits for the first nine months to about Pounds 55m, down from
Pounds 70m last time, largely because of problems in the US.
</TEXT>
