<HEADLINE>
FT  12 NOV 94 / International Company News: Japanese broker hit by one-off
Y32bn loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GERARD BAKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Tokyo Securities, a medium-sized stockbroker, yesterday announced it had
incurred an extraordinary loss of Y32bn (Dollars 326.4m) in unauthorised US
bond and currency transactions by one of its senior traders. The company
will report the loss across both halves of the current fiscal year which
ends next March.
The loss is almost as large as the brokerage's entire annual operating
revenues, which will reach Y33bn for the current fiscal year.
Last month, Tokyo Securities reported a first-half loss after tax of Y2.5bn,
on very thin equity trading volumes. That figure will now be revised down to
Y16.6bn. For the current full year, the company forecasts after-tax losses
of Y32.5bn, compared with last month's forecast profit of Y1.1bn, and 1993's
actual profit of Y1.3bn.
Tokyo Securities said the trader, who was not named, had acted beyond his
authority and taken significant positions in US bonds and currencies, and
was personally responsible for the loss. It said he would be punished
according to internal company rules.
The brokerage had net assets in March this year of Y94bn, and shareholders'
capital of Y86bn. It has branches in New York, Hong Kong, London and Zurich.
More than a quarter of its shares are owned by companies linked with Nikko
Securities, one of Japan's four largest brokerages.
</TEXT>
